{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/achilles-tendinopathy/diagnosis/diagnosis-of-achilles-tendon-rupture/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"34cf88b7-c8ff-55e8-b38f-76df8ac1f7bf","slug":"diagnosis-of-achilles-tendon-rupture","fullItemName":"Diagnosis of Achilles tendon rupture","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 36f1032c-bd6c-4d95-8d59-15666032e5a2 --><h2>When should I suspect Achilles tendon rupture?</h2><!-- end field 36f1032c-bd6c-4d95-8d59-15666032e5a2 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item e97050d1-6547-4e71-9b52-38d5e9344991 --><!-- begin field 257059bd-b573-4579-98cb-ee2cb8aeab40 --><ul><li><strong>Suspect Achilles tendon rupture if </strong><strong>the person describes:</strong><ul><li>A sudden pain in the back of the leg, which may be associated with an audible snap and occur during sporting activity or running. This may be described as being kicked or hit by a racquet.<ul><li>Note that approximately a third of people with complete tendon rupture do not complain of pain.</li></ul></li><li>Aching of the calf, swelling, mild bruising, and weakness when pushing off with the affected foot.<ul><li>Swelling and bruising are not a reliable sign as they may be mild.</li></ul></li><li>Difficulty with weight bearing.<ul><li>In some cases the person may be able to walk because other plantar flexors may mask the Achilles tendon injury.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Examine the person using Simmonds triad (angle of declination, palpation, and the calf squeeze test) to help exclude </strong><strong>Achilles tendon rupture:</strong><ul><li>Ask the person to lie prone with their feet over the edge of the examination couch:<ul><li>Look for an abnormal angle of declination — rupture of the Achilles tendon may lead to greater dorsiflexion of the injured ankle and foot compared with the uninjured limb.</li><li>Feel for a gap in the tendon. No gap may be felt because of local swelling or bleeding. Bruising may be seen.</li><li>Gently and sequentially squeeze the calf muscles — in acute rupture of the Achilles tendon the injured foot will typically remain in the neutral position when the calf is squeezed. </li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Be aware that diagnosis of chronic rupture may be difficult, because:<ul><li>Pain and swelling have often subsided and the gap may have filled with fibrous tissue.</li><li>Calf muscles may be wasted.</li><li>Other muscles may facilitate plantar flexion.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 257059bd-b573-4579-98cb-ee2cb8aeab40 --><!-- end item e97050d1-6547-4e71-9b52-38d5e9344991 -->","topic":{"id":"a4ec84b7-886a-5579-a133-17740dcc72c3","topicId":"544c0dd8-12b4-472f-8325-25f15b3092e3","topicName":"Achilles tendinopathy","slug":"achilles-tendinopathy","lastRevised":"Last revised in June 2020","chapters":[{"id":"342af048-69de-5cc6-83ef-2d9535909c69","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"f4364122-f06e-518b-b540-17c7f31d1e11","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"b099b421-395c-5c3e-a52a-08a168943a2d","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"43885ca6-3854-57e0-b673-d00e904a68d0","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"618c6e12-afee-5776-9b09-d249d2e5d4a6","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"cebb13f2-1c56-5eb8-bc8c-7826b141e1dc","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"ea10f3ef-0f07-5ca3-b9ba-c799e2c0ecae","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"c3f6243c-b2ef-5320-8fe9-974cc62e5088","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"c166d91e-6f69-5a9c-80b7-83af1faa167b","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"7c802a6f-65e8-5050-9068-f14ebff6e9d6","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"6c40895d-3868-5e4d-9c14-1